Part 1: Data

he Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) is a collaborative project between all of the states in the United States (US) and participating US territories and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). The BRFSS is administered and supported by CDC’s Population Health Surveillance Branch, under the Division of Population Health at the National Center for Chronic Disease Prevention and Health Promotion. BRFSS is an ongoing surveillance system designed to measure behavioral risk factors for the non-institutionalized adult population (18 years of age and older) residing in the US. The BRFSS was initiated in 1984, with 15 states collecting surveillance data on risk behaviors through monthly telephone interviews. Over time, the number of states participating in the survey increased; by 2001, 50 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, Guam, and the US Virgin Islands were participating in the BRFSS. Today, all 50 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and Guam collect data annually and American Samoa, Federated States of Micronesia, and Palau collect survey data over a limited point- in-time (usually one to three months). In this document, the term “state” is used to refer to all areas participating in BRFSS, including the District of Columbia, Guam, and the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico.

Data Gathering Year: 2013 Data Gathering Location: US states and the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and Guam Population in Focus: non-institutionalized adult population, aged 18 years or older, who reside in the US.

The Data Gathering Method: - Stratified Random sampling - state-specific data

Data Gathering Goals: - study preventive health practices - Study risk behaviors that are linked to chronic diseases, injuries, and preventable infectious diseases that affect the adult population

Study Type: - Observational Study

Generalization & Causality: - The results can be generalized to the adult population of the participating states. - Results must be investigated for implicit biases - This Study is based on Observational Study and Causal Inferences cannot be drawn from data.

Part 2: Research questions

Research question 1: General Health and Employment

Is there any relationship between People’s General Health (Genhlth) and their work (employ1) in the population of interest?

Why I am interested in this Question:

The first thing that comes to my mind is that having a job and dedicating a great portion of your time will enable you to be busy with matter not related to you and consequently, have more physical and mental activity, at the same time, have more relationships. I need also mention that being busy with something as a job, will give you goals, both short-term and long-term, while your income will allow you to be more confident and self-reliant, which is a positive feeling for many people.

So, in order to address this question, I analyzed 3 variables : employ1, genhlth, sex. Considering “Sex” helps me to compare the results in both sex and see if there is any relation with employment status and people’s sex.

Hypothesis: I guess that people with no job or less hours of work feel less healthy.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Research question 1:

q1 <- brfss2013 %>% select(sex, employ1, genhlth) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(sex), !is.na(employ1),!is.na(genhlth)) %>% 
  group_by(sex,employ1,genhlth) %>%   
  summarise(count=n()) %>%  
  mutate(perc=count/sum(count))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'sex', 'employ1'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(q1, aes(x = factor(employ1), y = perc*100, fill = factor(genhlth))) +
 geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  labs(x = "Employment Status", y = "Percentage", fill = "General Health") +
  theme(legend.key.height=unit(1, "cm"),axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust=1))+
  facet_grid(. ~  sex)

Findings: - It appears that people “unable to work” are the least group that feel less healthy. This is true for both sex groups. In general other groups with different types of employment feel better about their general health. - The other finding was about the the employment type " Self-employed“. Based on data and comparing to others, this groups demonstrated the highest reports about their general health as”Excellent“. - Despite the group of people”unable to work", other groups’ General Health reports are more positive (Good, Very Good and Execellent). In general, it can be inferred that the sample’s overall general health state is in a good shape.

With this exploration, my hypothesis is not completely proved to be correct, as we saw this outcome in only one group and that was related to people whom were unable to work.

Research question 2:

q2 <- brfss2013 %>% select(sex, X_state, genhlth) %>%
  filter(!is.na(sex), !is.na(X_state), !is.na(genhlth)) %>%
  group_by(sex, X_state, genhlth) %>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>% 
  mutate(perc=count/sum(count))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'sex', 'X_state'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(q2, aes(x = factor(X_state), y = perc*100, fill = factor(genhlth))) +
 geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  labs(x = "State", y = "Percentage", fill = "General Health") +
  theme(legend.key.height=unit(1, "cm"),axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust=1))+
  facet_grid(. ~  sex)

Findings:

  1. As I was assuming, there is a relationship between people’s living location and their General Health, and this variance in the sampled population is observable in the graph. There needs further research to measure this relationship in detail.
  2. On average, US poeple are feeling “Very Good” about their health, 32.1% of the participants in the servery.
  3. There is only few population that feel “poor” about their General Health, consisting 5.74% of the survey population.
  4. The General Health in the sample is also varies by Sex. For instance, Male Porto Rico people are feeling more Healthy Comparing to Porto Rico Female and this gap is observable in the graph.

Research question 3:

q3 <- brfss2013 %>% select(sex, educa, genhlth) %>%
  filter(!is.na(sex), !is.na(educa),!is.na(genhlth)) %>%
  group_by(sex,educa,genhlth) %>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>% 
  mutate(perc=count/sum(count))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'sex', 'educa'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
group_by(q3 , genhlth) %>% summarise(disp=mean(perc))
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   genhlth    disp
## * <fct>     <dbl>
## 1 Excellent 0.130
## 2 Very good 0.237
## 3 Good      0.312
## 4 Fair      0.212
## 5 Poor      0.110
ggplot(q3, aes(x = factor(educa), y = perc*100, fill = factor(genhlth))) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  labs(x = "Education", y = "Percentage", fill = "General Health") +
  theme(legend.key.height=unit(1, "cm"),axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust=1))+
  facet_grid(. ~  sex)

The relation between Education and General Health can be easily detected in the graph and it has significant variance.

Findings: 1. Higher Education can lead to more satisfaction from your General Health, as the most satisfied people are the one with Higher education or college degree. 2. Lower education or no education increases the chance of not having good feelings about your health. 3. While these findings may sound straight forward, further analysis is needed. For instance, there are chances the the income level would have a confound effect and its correlation with other factors like having access to better health services affect the result.
